            <strong>🇮🇳 India’s SEBI plans to regulate pre-listing IPO share trading</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          The Securities and Exchange Board of India (SEBI) is planning to regulate the trading of shares before the official listing. The body aims to curb the <a href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-22-01-2025-wn2-4-unofficial-black-market" target="_blank">unofficial “black market”</a> for IPO shares. Chairperson Madhabi Puri Buch stated that SEBI may introduce a system that allows investors who receive IPO allotments to trade their entitled shares before the IPO. The country is home to one of the biggest IPO markets, with over 300 companies raising over $20 billion through IPOs in 2024.
        </p>
