              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the Ricardian equivalence?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-22-3.png" alt="What is the Ricardian equivalence?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000"> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The Ricardian equivalence is an economic theory proposed by David Ricardo. It suggests that government borrowing and taxation are equivalent in their impact on an economy because rational consumers anticipate future tax increases to repay public debt. As a result, they adjust their behavior by saving more to offset the expected tax burden leaving overall demand in the economy unchanged.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">For example, if a government funds a stimulus program through borrowing instead of raising taxes, consumers may reduce their current spending, anticipating that higher taxes will be required later to pay off the debt. This offsets the stimulative effect of government spending, rendering fiscal policy ineffective in boosting economic growth.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">While Ricardian Equivalence provides an interesting theoretical perspective, its real-world applicability is debated as not all consumers are perfectly rational or fully informed about government fiscal policies.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
